34:22.326 --> 34:29.967 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
For the "PBS NewsHour," I'm
Malcolm Brabant
in Norway.

34:30.001 --> 34:43.314 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: Decades ago,
China began
a practice that human rights
advocates and

34:43.347 --> 34:48.619 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
medical ethicists condemned:
taking organs,
such as kidneys and livers, from
executed

34:48.653 --> 34:52.123 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
prisoners to transplant into
people who needed
them.

34:52.156 --> 34:54.892 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The Chinese government says it's
reformed
the practice.

34:54.926 --> 34:58.262 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Now they say they only recover
organs from
volunteers.

34:58.296 --> 35:00.698 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
But some say the practice
continues.

35:00.731 --> 35:04.969 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Hari Sreenivasan and producer
Dan Sagalyn
have the story.

35:05.002 --> 35:10.241 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: This is when a
life is renewed.

35:10.274 --> 35:15.313 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
A transplant surgeon, seen here,
removes a
kidney from a volunteer donor
and inserts

35:15.346 --> 35:17.849 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
it into someone whose kidneys
are failing.

35:17.882 --> 35:21.986 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In most cases, patients who need
a new organ
have to wait months or years
before one is

35:22.019 --> 35:23.754 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
available.

35:23.788 --> 35:27.625 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But this man, who told us he had
end-stage
kidney disease 11 years ago,
could wait no

35:27.658 --> 35:29.427 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
longer.

35:29.460 --> 35:31.562 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MAN (through translator): I was
on dialysis
already two years, and I was
constantly going

35:31.596 --> 35:32.663 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
downhill.

35:32.697 --> 35:34.699 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: We met him in
Vancouver,
Canada.

35:34.732 --> 35:39.270 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He asked that we conceal his
identity by hiding
his face and replacing his voice
to protect

35:39.303 --> 35:40.671 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
his privacy.

35:40.705 --> 35:42.540 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MAN (through translator): They
called these
people the living dead.

35:42.573 --> 35:44.408 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
You just haven't died yet, but
you're gone.

35:44.442 --> 35:48.713 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Because of his
age and rare
blood type, he says he would
have died before

35:48.746 --> 35:51.282 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
reaching the top of the waiting
list for a
new kidney.

35:51.315 --> 35:57.421 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, urged by family and friends,
he went to
China's capital, Beijing, in
2006.

35:57.455 --> 36:00.124 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Within one week, he received a
new kidney.

36:00.158 --> 36:03.227 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
He says he paid $10,000 for the
transplant.

36:03.261 --> 36:06.898 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In Canada, it would have been
free, since
the government pays for health
care.

36:06.931 --> 36:12.904 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
In the U.S., the average
hospital charge for
a kidney transplant is $150,000.

36:12.937 --> 36:16.774 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Traveling to another country for
this kind
of surgery is called transplant
tourism.

36:16.807 --> 36:17.975 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
MAN (through translator): I went
there dead.

36:18.009 --> 36:19.744 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
I came back alive.

36:19.777 --> 36:23.047 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: On average, 22
people die
every day in the United States
waiting for

36:23.080 --> 36:24.849 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
a transplant.

36:24.882 --> 36:29.854 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The median wait time for a lung
here is four
months, a heart almost a year,
and a kidney

36:29.887 --> 36:31.722 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
two years.

36:31.756 --> 36:35.927 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Transplant tourists
understandably have been
drawn to other countries by
promises of little

36:35.960 --> 36:37.495 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
to no wait.

36:37.528 --> 36:41.465 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It's not just Canada that
generates transplant
tourists to China.

36:41.499 --> 36:46.037 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
On the other side of the world,
at about the
same time, an Israeli doctor had
a patient

36:46.070 --> 36:47.772 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
who also needed a transplant.

36:47.805 --> 36:49.574 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
DR.

36:49.607 --> 36:51.409 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JACOB LAVEE, Israel Society of
Transplantation:
Back in 2005, a patient of mine
came to me

36:51.442 --> 36:56.747 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
one day and told me, doc, I'm
fed up waiting
here in Israel for a suitable
heart donor

36:56.781 --> 37:01.886 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to become available, and I was
told -- that's
what he told me -- by my
insurance company

37:01.919 --> 37:07.225 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that I should go to China
because they have
scheduled me to undergo heart
transplantation.

37:07.258 --> 37:12.063 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And he specified a specific date
two weeks
ahead of time.

37:12.096 --> 37:16.667 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Heart surgeon
Dr. Jacob
Lavee is president of the Israel
Society of

37:16.701 --> 37:18.536 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Transplantation.

37:18.569 --> 37:21.572 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
While kidney transplants can
involve obtaining
a kidney from a living donor,
that is not

37:21.606 --> 37:22.773 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
the case with a heart
transplant.

37:22.807 --> 37:24.609 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
DR.

37:24.642 --> 37:27.878 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JACOB LAVEE: If a patient was
promised to
undergo a heart transplant on a
specific date,

37:27.912 --> 37:33.618 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
this could only mean that the --
those who
promised that knew ahead of time
when his

37:33.651 --> 37:35.386 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
potential donor would be dead.

37:35.419 --> 37:38.723 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Human rights
investigator
Ethan Gutmann and lawyer David
Matas have

37:38.756 --> 37:42.093 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
testified before Congress about
China's transplant
system.

37:42.126 --> 37:45.763 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DAVID MATAS, Attorney: It is
unconscionable
to kill a healthy, innocent
person so that

37:45.796 --> 37:47.632 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
