37:47.665 --> 37:51.969 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: They say they
know how organs
in China become available with
no wait time.

37:52.003 --> 37:57.108 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DAVID MATAS: They have obviously
got a lot
of people sitting around waiting
to be killed

37:57.141 --> 37:58.909 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
for a transplant.

37:58.943 --> 38:02.246 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And they are just picking the
right person
to be killed depending on who
the patient

38:02.280 --> 38:04.181 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
is.

38:04.215 --> 38:07.418 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Matas and
Gutmann say Chinese
doctors have coordinated with
Chinese prison

38:07.451 --> 38:14.692 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
officials, and inmate executions
take place
when patients are in need of
organs.

38:14.725 --> 38:18.696 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Medical professionals and human
rights advocates
say this practice violates the
prisoner's

38:18.729 --> 38:19.997 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
human rights.

38:20.031 --> 38:24.001 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
However, this is how one Chinese
doctor justified
the practice.

38:24.035 --> 38:26.070 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
This video was produced by the
Chinese government.

38:26.103 --> 38:28.039 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
DR.

38:28.072 --> 38:29.340 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HE XIAOSHUN, First Affiliated
Hospital (through
translator): To apply the
traditional Chinese

38:29.373 --> 38:31.542 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
way of thinking, the prisoners
committed sins
in their lives.

38:31.575 --> 38:35.746 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
If we let them donate their
organs, well,
in a sense, they are offering
salvation.

38:35.780 --> 38:37.782 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
They can atone for their crime
with that opportunity.

38:37.815 --> 38:43.087 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: At a press
conference in
2005, China's vice minister of
health, Huang

38:43.120 --> 38:46.757 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Jiefu, admitted the government
took organs
from executed prisoners.

38:46.791 --> 38:52.763 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But, in 2014, Huang Jiefu, who
is now leading
the reform efforts in China,
declared that,

38:52.797 --> 38:58.969 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
starting in 2015, China would
stop using organs
from executed prisoners.

38:59.003 --> 39:03.941 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But Matas and Gutmann believe
they have evidence
that this practice still
continues.

39:03.974 --> 39:09.246 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
They say inmates on death row
include prisoners
of conscience, such as
practitioners of Falun

39:09.280 --> 39:13.551 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Gong who become unwilling
sources for organs.

39:13.584 --> 39:18.489 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Falun Gong is a form of Chinese
meditation
and exercise with a spiritual
underpinning.

39:18.522 --> 39:24.095 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Since 1999, the Chinese
government has cracked
down on Falun Gong, charging it
with being

39:24.128 --> 39:27.798 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
an unregistered religion and
cult that aims
to subvert the state.

39:27.832 --> 39:32.937 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DAVID MATAS: We interviewed
Falun Gong who
got out of prison, got out of
China, systematically

39:32.970 --> 39:37.308 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
blood-tested, organ-examined,
not for their
health -- they were being
tortured -- and

39:37.341 --> 39:43.347 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
only the types of examinations
relevant to
transplantation.

39:43.381 --> 39:45.649 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Wang Chunying
and Yin Liping
practice Falun Gong.

39:45.683 --> 39:49.053 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Both say they were detained a
number of times
between 1999 and 2009.

39:49.086 --> 39:54.959 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WANG CHUNYING, Former Prisoner
(through translator):
In 2008, I was forced to take a
blood draw.

39:54.992 --> 39:57.395 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
The atmosphere was very tense
and horrific.

39:57.428 --> 40:01.031 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I thought this blood draw must
be related
to looking for matching organs.

40:01.065 --> 40:03.901 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: The Chinese
government might
say, we just needed more blood.

40:03.934 --> 40:04.902 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
That is all.

40:04.935 --> 40:05.903 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
We didn't take her organs.

40:05.936 --> 40:07.872 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
We didn't do anything to her
body.

40:07.905 --> 40:11.208 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We just took blood to make sure
there wasn't
an infection in the yard.

40:11.242 --> 40:15.346 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
How do you know that the
government wanted
your blood for any other
reasons?

40:15.379 --> 40:17.882 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
WANG CHUNYING (through
translator): Because
the living conditions were
terrible in the

40:17.915 --> 40:19.283 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
reeducation camp.

40:19.316 --> 40:21.552 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They didn't care about whether
we lived or
died.

40:21.585 --> 40:25.256 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
YIN LIPING, Former Prisoner
(through translator):
Once, I was forced to take a
blood draw.

40:25.289 --> 40:30.895 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
There were multiple times of
other tests,
such as MRI, ultrasound and
chest X-ray.

40:30.928 --> 40:36.100 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Gutmann says
he's interviewed
ethnic minorities from Tibet and
Xinjiang

40:36.133 --> 40:40.204 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
who all tell similar stories
about medical
examinations while in prison.

40:40.237 --> 40:42.673 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ETHAN GUTMANN, Human Rights
Investigator:
When you start to hear the same
description

40:42.706 --> 40:46.343 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
of an examination in a
completely different
language from a completely
different group,

40:46.377 --> 40:51.615 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
but it's the same examination,
this is one
of the big tipoffs that this is
really directed

40:51.649 --> 40:55.619 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
towards China's enemies, its
political and
religious enemies.

40:55.653 --> 41:00.624 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Matas and
Gutmann say there's
another possible motive driving
this practice:

41:00.658 --> 41:02.593 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
profit.

41:02.626 --> 41:09.133 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In the past, some Chinese
hospitals even advertised
the costs of new organs, $98,000
to $130,000

41:09.166 --> 41:13.838 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
for a liver, $130,000 to
$160,000 for a heart.

41:13.871 --> 41:19.477 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
By reviewing Chinese medical
publications,
hospital Web site data, and
making calls to

41:19.510 --> 41:26.383 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
hospitals, Gutmann and Matas
estimate there
could be 60,000 to 100,000
transplants still

41:26.417 --> 41:28.719 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
taking place each year in China.

41:28.752 --> 41:31.188 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
The Chinese government rejects
these accusations.

41:31.222 --> 41:37.061 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In 2016, it says there were just
over 13,000
transplants performed in the
country.

41:37.094 --> 41:41.765 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Compare that to the United
States that had
33,000 transplants last year.

41:41.799 --> 41:46.237 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In an e-mail to the "NewsHour,"
a spokesman
from the Chinese Embassy in
Washington, D.C.,

41:46.270 --> 41:51.208 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
writes: "The Chinese government
firmly abide
by the internationally
recognized ethical

41:51.242 --> 41:56.881 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
principles about organ
transplantation, and
adhere to the voluntary organ
donation after

41:56.914 --> 41:59.049 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
the death of Chinese citizens."

41:59.083 --> 42:03.387 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We asked if political prisoners
were singled
out for execution for their
organs.

42:03.420 --> 42:06.290 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
The embassy didn't respond to
this question.

42:06.323 --> 42:11.362 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Chinese officials do say, since
2015, they
no longer recover organs from
prisoners.

42:11.395 --> 42:16.400 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Dr. Huang Jiefu, who is leading
reform efforts,
acknowledged in an interview
with a Chinese

42:16.433 --> 42:19.370 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
newspaper progress has been
slow.

42:19.403 --> 42:23.941 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
"Our use of death row prisoner
organs before
the establishment of a citizen
organ donation

42:23.974 --> 42:29.380 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
system was an act of desperation
to save the
lives of patients suffering
organ failure.

42:29.413 --> 42:33.751 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
When the citizen donation system
was set up,
we abolished this source of
organs as quickly

42:33.784 --> 42:35.686 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
as possible."

42:35.719 --> 42:39.890 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In February of this year, at a
Vatican conference
on organ trafficking, Chinese
medical leaders

42:39.924 --> 42:46.297 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
agreed that using organs from
executed prisoners
is a crime and should be
condemned worldwide.

42:46.330 --> 42:50.568 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
A number of American doctors who
have been
to China say they believe the
country has

42:50.601 --> 42:55.239 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
taken major steps to stop the
practice of
taking organs from executed
prisoners.

42:55.272 --> 42:57.074 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
DR.

42:57.107 --> 42:59.009 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
FRANCIS DELMONICO, World Health
Organization:
The reports that we get from
Canada or the

42:59.043 --> 43:05.215 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
United States or from the Middle
East of individuals
undergoing transplantation,
that's markedly

43:05.249 --> 43:07.952 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
reduced, but it has not
completely stopped.

43:07.985 --> 43:11.755 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Dr. Francis
Delmonico is
an adviser to the World Health
Organization

43:11.789 --> 43:18.395 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and former president of the
Transplantation
Society.

43:18.429 --> 43:23.867 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He's leading the international
effort to help
China establish a new system of
organ donation.

43:23.901 --> 43:29.073 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
When did you first become aware
that China
might be executing people for
their organs?

43:29.106 --> 43:30.074 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
DR.

43:30.107 --> 43:31.075 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
FRANCIS DELMONICO: 2005.

43:31.108 --> 43:32.076 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
HARI SREENIVASAN: How?

43:32.109 --> 43:33.877 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
DR.

43:33.911 --> 43:38.248 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
FRANCIS DELMONICO: I was invited
to the Peking
Union Medical College by Jiefu
Huang, who

43:38.282 --> 43:40.417 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
was, at the time, vice minister
of health.

43:40.451 --> 43:42.586 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And he was a liver transplant
surgeon.

43:42.620 --> 43:48.092 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And he said to me, "Frank, this
is -- we have
got a horrendous problem, and I
need your

43:48.125 --> 43:49.093 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
help."

43:49.126 --> 43:51.729 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Individuals in China were being
executed.

43:51.762 --> 43:56.700 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And those were the -- they
became the source
of organs for many people from
around the

43:56.734 --> 44:02.072 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
world going to China, as many as
11,000 transplants
being performed, and this is in
2006.

44:02.106 --> 44:06.944 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: While some
doctors like
Huang Jiefu wanted this practice
stopped,

44:06.977 --> 44:11.315 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
others who were making money
from organ trafficking
didn't, according to Delmonico.

44:11.348 --> 44:16.887 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
To put pressure on China, a
number of medical
associations and journals
launched a boycott,

44:16.920 --> 44:23.260 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
beginning in 2006, banning
Chinese research
papers that relied on data from
executed prisoners.

44:23.293 --> 44:27.431 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
At the same time, Delmonico and
other doctors
helped China build a new and
legitimate system

44:27.464 --> 44:33.003 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
for organ recovery, similar to
the system
in the U.S., requiring consent
and only from

44:33.037 --> 44:35.939 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
live or deceased donors in
hospitals.

44:35.973 --> 44:40.044 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Has China stopped harvesting
organs from people
that they have executed, that
they are executing?

44:40.077 --> 44:41.111 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
DR.

44:41.145 --> 44:43.347 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
FRANCIS DELMONICO: I don't know
that for certain.

44:43.380 --> 44:45.949 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
So I can say to you that it's
markedly reduced.

44:45.983 --> 44:49.253 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But can I assure you or the rest
of the world
that it's completely stopped?

44:49.286 --> 44:51.021 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
I can't.

44:51.055 --> 44:54.558 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Delmonico says
there's a
new generation of doctors in
China that want

44:54.591 --> 44:59.596 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and embrace the reforms that are
taking place
in China's transplantation
system.

44:59.630 --> 45:04.368 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But human rights investigator
Ethan Gutmann
says China is still killing
prisoners and

45:04.401 --> 45:06.170 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
taking their organs.

45:06.203 --> 45:10.441 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ETHAN GUTMANN: Our report shows
tremendous
continuity over time, even while
they're -- the

45:10.474 --> 45:13.043 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Chinese are making completely
different statements
about this.

45:13.077 --> 45:16.213 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Leading
experts to call
for inspections of Chinese
hospitals.

45:16.246 --> 45:17.981 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
DR.

45:18.015 --> 45:23.220 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JACOB LAVEE: What needs to be
done now is
an international committees of
transplant

45:23.253 --> 45:28.358 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
experts that will be allowed to
visit China
and verify the source of these
organs.

45:28.392 --> 45:32.362 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
HARI SREENIVASAN: In his
desperation, this
man says he didn't think about
where his new

45:32.396 --> 45:35.966 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
kidney came from, and, looking
back, that
he has no regrets.

45:35.999 --> 45:38.001 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MAN (through translator): It's
given me a
new outlook on life.

45:38.035 --> 45:41.305 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I had an opportunity to see my
children graduate
from universities.

45:41.338 --> 45:43.407 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I have a happy life with my
wife.

45:43.440 --> 45:48.746 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: For the "PBS
NewsHour,"
I'm Hari Sreenivasan.

45:48.779 --> 45:58.789 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: Memorial Day,
of course,
is the traditional kickoff to
summer.

45:58.822 --> 46:02.493 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And for many of us, that means
time to catch
up on our reading.

46:02.526 --> 46:06.396 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Jeffrey Brown brings us some
suggestions from
our "NewsHour" Bookshelf.

46:06.430 --> 46:09.166 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Some of us go for
lighter fare.

46:09.199 --> 46:13.804 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Some catch up on missed
readings, and others
go for rereadings of old
favorites.

46:13.837 --> 46:18.008 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We get some summer picks from
two prominent
writers who also own bookstores.

46:18.041 --> 46:22.212 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Louise Erdrich is author of 15
novels, as
well as nonfiction and poetry.

46:22.246 --> 46:24.081 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
Her most recent novel is
"LaRose."

46:24.114 --> 46:28.452 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Prior to that, "The Round House"
was winner
of the National Book Award for
Fiction.

46:28.485 --> 46:31.622 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
She's the owner of Birchbark
Books in Minneapolis.

46:31.655 --> 46:35.726 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And Emma Straub's novels include
"Modern Lovers"
and "The Vacationers."

46:35.759 --> 46:40.597 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
She is co-owner with her husband
of the Brooklyn,
New York bookstore Books Are
Magic.

46:40.631 --> 46:42.366 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
And welcome to both of you.

46:42.399 --> 46:47.104 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I'm guessing that you both are
year-round
readers, but let me start with
you, Louise.

46:47.137 --> 46:51.775 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Does summer reading have a
particular resonance
for you, the things you go
after?

46:51.809 --> 46:53.911 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
LOUISE ERDRICH, Author,
"LaRose": It does.

46:53.944 --> 47:01.685 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I'm here in Minnesota, so I go
to the lake,
and I bring a load of books, and
I sink into

47:01.718 --> 47:05.823 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
them, and read wherever I am
around a lake.

47:05.856 --> 47:06.957 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
That's how we do it.

47:06.990 --> 47:07.991 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: That's how you do
it in Minnesota,
huh?

47:08.025 --> 47:10.294 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
LOUISE ERDRICH: And that's how
we do it.

47:10.327 --> 47:11.528 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
It's reading on the dock.

47:11.562 --> 47:14.431 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
It's reading if you're floating
in the lake.

47:14.464 --> 47:17.067 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
It's reading if it rains,
everything.

47:17.100 --> 47:24.908 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
That's where you read, and you
can read yourself
into a sort of stupor, which you
then solve

47:24.942 --> 47:27.711 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
with a lot of grilled meat.

47:27.744 --> 47:29.246 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(LAUGHTER)

47:29.279 --> 47:32.649 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: And Emma Straub,
what do you
do in the summer for reading?

47:32.683 --> 47:35.886 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
EMMA STRAUB, Author, "Modern
Lovers": Well,
starting this summer, I'm just
going to go

47:35.919 --> 47:41.158 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to Louise's house by the lake
with a stack
of books and wait for grilled
meat.

47:41.191 --> 47:42.860 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
LOUISE ERDRICH: It will be
great.

47:42.893 --> 47:44.261 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Yes, it's how it happens.

47:44.294 --> 47:45.696 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
EMMA STRAUB: It sounds perfect.

47:45.729 --> 47:47.531 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
It sounds perfect.

47:47.564 --> 47:53.737 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I guess I have always thought of
summer reading
as like the stack of books I
would bring with

47:53.770 --> 47:58.809 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
me to summer camp, you know,
when you have
